deck: The "ugly" niece of Herman and Lily Munster from the 1960s TV series The Munsters.
description:
Marilyn remains steadfastly oblivious to the idea there is anything bizarre or frightening about her Uncle Herman and Aunt Lily, her cousin Eddie, or Grandpa, and she has become quite angry with anyone who "insults" the Munsters by pointing out their monster nature. Naturally, she is convinced that she is the ugly member of the family because she doesn't resemble her revived corpse uncle or her vampire aunt.

Marilyn's parents were never named in the series. However, it was revealed in the series that Herman had been built by the famous Dr. Frankenstein (making him the younger brother of the Frankenstein monster) and soon after adopted by the Munster family, a family of ordinary humans happily involved with mad science and magic; therefore, Marilyn must be the offspring of one of Herman's adopted brothers.

Marilyn Munster shares with her extended family a supernatural invulnerability, happily making meals of substances that would kill any ordinary human being and taking no damage from things that would wound an ordinary person, such as electrocution, being blown up, and drinking furiously boiling liquids. Despite her very human appearance, it is quite possible that she is no more human than are the rest of her family.

deck: Ruler of the Ichinohei clan.
description:
Origin

A Japanese pilot, Kudusai fought during World War II against Russian pilots. His plane was shot down above Russia. He managed to land his plane and surveyed his surroundings. Quickly, he met a Russian woman named Tasha, who lived alone on a farm with her infant daughter Anna. They fell in love, despite Kudusai having a family in Japan. Kudusai repaired his plane and had finished it, just as Russian soldiers invaded the farm. Tasha was shot down. Kudusai managed to rescue Anna and took her back in his plane to Japan, where she was raised by him and his wife as their own, alongside their son Shoji.

Japan had attacked the United States during Kudusai's time in Russia. The United States retalliated and eventually Japan surrendered, but not before Kudusai's wife had died. After the war, Kudusai met the American captain Jerome Feeple. Jerome set up a plan to exterminate the rats that plagued Kudusai's town and made Kudusai his administrator.

Several years later, Kudusai hired an ambitious associate named Kenjo Rivalsan. After a while, they had a business argument and Kenjo left. Several days later Jerome also left, harving served his duty in Japan.

Kudusai had gained control over his clan. Shoji had married a woman named Hana and had two daughters. Kudusai's adopted daughter Anna had grown up and was trained by Kudusai to be a ninja.

When Kudusai discovered a rat in his basement, he sent for his old partner Feeple. Feeple sent his son, Bob Feeple. The moment Anna and Bob met, they fell in love and married in Japan. It was arranged that the oldest son of the Feeple would be promised to Kudusai's oldest granddaughter, Itchy Koo Ichinohei. Several months later, Jeremy Feeple was born.

description:
Creation

John King was created by writers Andrew Kreisberg and Ben Sokolowski and artist Daniel Sampere, and seems to be a play off Robin Hood's enemy King John.

Major Story Arcs

Kingdom

John King is an industrialist and the third richest man in America behind Bruce Wayne and Lex Luthor, he managed to create a huge following of "subjects" through a combination of bribery, blackmail, and possibly torture. He is Mia Dearden's step-father, but she witnessed him murder her mother and ran away, eventually being saved by Green Arrow, King now wants Green Arrow dead and he already knows that he is Oliver Queen. During a failed attempt on Oliver's life, Kings men are able to kidnap both Mia and Ollie's girlfriend/business manager.
